<paragraph blockId="121.[151,1437,1803,2035]" pageId="121" pageNumber="122">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,371,1803,1827]" pageId="121" pageNumber="122">FIGURES 280–286</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName authority="Buck &amp; Marshall, 2009" authorityName="Buck &amp; Marshall" authorityYear="2009" box="[386,549,1804,1827]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Leptocera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="121" pageNumber="122" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="plax" status="sp.n.">
<emphasis box="[386,549,1804,1827]" italics="true" pageId="121" pageNumber="122">Leptocera plax</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[557,608,1804,1827]" pageId="121" pageNumber="122" rank="species">sp.n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
(Ecuador). Male terminalia (phallus and postgonites omitted): (280) lateral; (281) posterior; (282) ventral; (283) sternite 5. Female terminalia: (284) dorsal; (285) spermathecae; (286) ventral. aps—anterior process of anterior section of surstylus; ce—cercus; cp—finger-like process of cercus; ep—epandrium; ha—hypandrial apodeme; hy—hypandrium; pa—phallapodeme; pssb—posterior section of surstylus, basal part; pssc—ditto, connection between basal and distal part; pssd—ditto, distal part; S—sternite; sc—enlarged scales; se—subepandrial sclerite; T—tergite (female tergite 8 divided into two halves); vls—ventral lobe of anterior section of surstylus.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<subSubSection pageId="122" pageNumber="123" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="122.[151,1436,151,835]" pageId="122" pageNumber="123">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,332,499,525]" pageId="122" pageNumber="123">Etymology</emphasis>
. The species name is a noun in apposition and refers to the flat, plateau-like ventral lobe of the anterior section of the surstylus (Gr. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Buck &amp; Marshall" authorityYear="2009" box="[580,630,538,563]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Leptocera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="122" pageNumber="123" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="plax">
<emphasis box="[580,630,538,563]" italics="true" pageId="122" pageNumber="123">plax</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
: plate, tablet).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="122" pageNumber="123" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="122.[151,1436,151,835]" pageId="122" pageNumber="123">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,352,576,602]" pageId="122" pageNumber="123">Distribution</emphasis>
. Presently known only from a small area of the Andean foothills in 
<collectingRegion box="[1143,1321,577,603]" country="Ecuador" name="Napo" pageId="122" pageNumber="123">Napo Province</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1332,1431,577,603]" name="Ecuador" pageId="122" pageNumber="123">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
, at elevations between 1,500 and 
<quantity box="[533,632,616,642]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.2" pageId="122" pageNumber="123" unit="m" value="2200.0">2,200 m</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="122" pageNumber="123" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="122.[151,1436,151,835]" pageId="122" pageNumber="123">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,331,654,680]" pageId="122" pageNumber="123">Discussion</emphasis>
. This is the only species of this group known from South America. It differs in a number of ways from the two Central American species, notably by the absence of the ventral posteroapical midtibial bristle, armature of male sternite 5 (resembling the teeth of a predator’s jaw), the separate sternite 8 (not fused to epandrium), slender medial process of male cercus and other less conspicuous details of the male and female terminalia.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
